<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-01">
  <title>Early Number Systems and Counting (1.1-1.3)</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Written-number-systems">
    <title>Written Number Systems</title>
    
    <p>
      The earliest evidence of mathematics is a bone found in the village of Ishago in the Democratic Republic on the Congo, which is over 8,000 years old. he markings in the bone are believed to have been tally marks; however, there are patterns in the bone that suggest that more mathematics than just counting is recorded here. For example, one row of the bone contains markings for the prime numbers between 10 and 20. 
    </p>

    <p>
      The Inca built the largest empire in pre-Columbian America. They ruled over a vast landscape that included mountains, deserts, and rain forests. They kept their empire together despite lacking the wheel, pack animals, or writing. Instead of using marking to record numbers, the Inca used knotted strings called Quipu. According to their positions on the string, the knots could signify units, tens, hundreds, thousands, ten thousands or hundred thousands.
    </p>

    <p>
      Written number systems are a culmination of these earlier developments. Tally marks like those on the Ishango bone where first used to record information. Over time more complex recording devices like the quipu were invented. Before the appearance of such devices, there must have been an efficient system of spoken numbers founded on the idea of base to enable numbers to be arranged in efficient groups.
    </p>

    <p>
      In a base system, some number <m>b</m> is selected as the base. Names are assigned to numbers <m>1, 2, \ldots, b</m> and larger numbers are given by combinations of the number names already selected.
    </p>

    <p>
      Many different bases have been used by various cultures throughout history. Here are a several of the more common ones.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Base 2- Used by certain tribes of central Africa
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Base 5- Used by some South American tribes as well as by the Yukaghirs of Siberia.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Base 10- Used in modern mathematics. Also used by Egyptians, Inca, Chinese, Indians, and others.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Base 20- Used by several Native American tribes, most famously the Maya.
          </p>
        </li>
        <p>
          Base 60- Used by ancient Babylonians.
        </p>
      </ul>
    </p>



  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Simple-Grouping-Systems">
    <title>Simple Grouping Systems</title>

    <p>
      There are many types of base systems even among systems sharing the same base. One type is known as a <term>simple grouping system</term>.
    </p>

    <p>
      In a simple grouping system, some number <m>b</m> is selected as a base and symbols are adopted for <m>1, b, b^2, \ldots</m>. A number is expressed by using the symbols additively, where each symbol is repeated the required number of times.
    </p>

    <p>
      An example of this type of system is found in the early Egyptian hieroglyphic system. This is a base 10 system.
    </p>

    <p>
      Each picture represents the value of the number. To express multiples of the number you repeat the symbol that many times. For example to express the number <m>300,000</m> you would draw three tadpoles.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Write <m>120,247</m> using Egyptian numerals.
    </p>

    <p>
      Another example of a simple grouping system is Roman numerals. Unlike Egyptian numerals which are multiples of 10, Roman numerals are multiples of 5. In modern use of Roman numerals a smaller numeral before a larger one represents subtraction. For example IV means <m>5-1=4</m>; however, the ancient Romans did not do this.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Write <m>2024</m> using Roman numerals
    </p>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Multiplicative-Grouping-Systems">
    <title>Multiplicative Grouping Systems</title>

    <p>
      In a multiplicative grouping system, after a base <m>b</m> is selected, symbols are chosen for <m>1, 2, \ldots, b-1</m> and a second set of symbols are adopted for <m>b, b^2, b^3, \ldots</m>. The symbol of the 2 sets are employed multiplicatively to show how many units of the higher groups are needed.
    </p>

    <p>
      As an example of this let <m>a = 10</m> <m>b=100</m> and <m>c=1000</m>. Then we would express the number 7453 as <m>7c4b5a3</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      The traditional Chinese numeral system is a multiplicative grouping system with base 10.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Let <m>a = 10</m> <m>b=100</m> and <m>c=1000</m>. How would you express the number <m>9268</m> in this system?
    </p>
    
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Ciphered-Grouping-Systems">
    <title>Ciphered Grouping Systems</title>

    <p>
      In a ciphered numeral system, after base <m>b</m> has been selected, sets of symbols are adopted for <m>1, 2, \ldots, b-1, b, 2b, 3b, \ldots (b-1)b, b^2, 2b^2, 3 b^2, \ldots (b-1)b^2</m> and so on.
    </p>

    <p>
      A ciphered numeral system requires more memorization of symbols, but representing numbers is compact.
    </p>

    <p>
      An example of the ciphered numeral system is the Greek numeral system which uses the letters of the Greek alphabet as symbols as well as some additions from the obsolete Phoenician alphabet. 
    </p>


    <p>
      Because the system was of the additive type, every integer from <m>1</m> to <m>999</m> could be represented using at most 3 letters.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Write the number <m>534</m> using the Greek numeral system.
    </p>

    <p>
      For larger numbers an accent mark to the lower left means to multiply the number by <m>1000</m>. So <m>_{'}\beta</m> means <m>2000</m> not <m>2</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      An M (for Myriad) next to a number means to multiply by <m>10,000</m>. So <m>M\beta</m> means <m>20,000</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Write the number <m>34,129</m> using the Greek numeral system.
    </p>

    <p>
      Because the Greek numeral system uses letters, each word and name has an associated number. For example the name Maria (<m>\mu\alpha\rho\iota\alpha</m>) has the associated number <m>40+1+100+10+1 = 152</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the meaning behind the number of the beast mentioned in the Biblical book of Revelation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          ``Let him who hath understanding calculate the number of the beast, for it is the number of a man: His number is 666''
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      -- Revelation 13:18
    </p>

    <p>
      Many people have been proposed for the identity of this man. For example, the Renaissance mathematician Michael Stifel gave the following argument to show that Pope Leo X was the antichrist.
    </p>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            In Latin, Leo X is written as LEO DECIMVS. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Removing all the letters that are not Roman numerals leaves LDCIMV which adds up to <m>1656</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Because there are 10 letters in LEO DECIMVS and M is the first letter in Mysterium the value for the letter M should be replaced with <m>10</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
          This gives a sum of <m>666</m>, the number of the beast.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      In the 2001 book <em>Science Askew</em> authors Donald Simanek and John Holden gave a similar proof that Barney the Dinosaur is the antichrist.
    </p>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Barney is well described as a CUTE PURPLE DINOSAUR
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Since the Latin alphabet used <em>V</em> instead of <em>U</em> the above phrase is CVTE PVRPLE DINOSAVR
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Remove the letters that are not Roman numerals to get CVVLDIV which adds up to <m>666</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    
  </subsection>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-Positional-Numeral-Systems">
  <title>Positional Numeral Systems</title>

  <p>
    Modern mathematics uses a positional numeral system with base 10. In a positional numeral system, after a base <m>b</m> has been selected, symbols are adopted for <m>0,1,2, \ldots, b-1</m>. These symbols are called the digits of the system.
  </p>

  <p>
    Any whole number <m>N</m> can be written uniquely in the form 
    <md>
      N= a_n b^n + a_{n-1}b^{n-1} + \ldots + a_1 b + a_0
    </md>
    and the number <m>N</m> is written using the sequence of basic symbols <m>a_n a_{n-1}\ldots a_1 a_0</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    For example, <m>29,608 = 2\cdot 10^4 + 9 \cdot 10^3 + 6 \cdot 10^2 + 0 \cdot 10 + 8</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    Another example of a positional number system is the Mayan numeral system which is (mostly) a base-20 system. The Mayan numeral system uses the following digits.
  </p>




  <p>
    In a pure base-20 system the positional values would be <m>1, 20, 20^2, 20^3, \ldots</m>; however in the  Mayan system the positional values are <m>1, 20, 20 \cdot 18, 20^2 \cdot 18, \ldots</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is believed that the reason for this is because the Mayan year consisted of 360 days and <m>20\cdot 18 = 360</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    In addition, Mayan numerals are written vertically with larger positional values on top.
  </p>

  <p>
    To express a number using Mayan numerals use the process of division and remainder to expand the number and obtain the digits.
  </p>

  <p>
    Example: Write the number <m>5,981</m> using Mayan numerals.
  </p>

  <p>
    Example: Write the number <m>64,128</m> using Mayan numerals.
  </p>

  <p>
    Another positional numeral system is the Kaktovik Inupiaq numerals. The Kaktovik Inupiaq numerals were invented in 1998 by a group of middle school children in Kaktovik, Alaska to create symbols for the Inupiaq language which is base 20.
  </p>

  <p>
    The ancient Babylonians used clay tablets to record information. They would scratch markings on these tablets, which today is called <term>cuneiform</term>. The Babylonian positional number system is the oldest positional number system that we know of. It is a sexagesimal (Base 60) system with place values <m>1</m>,<m>60</m>,<m>60^2= 3600</m>, <m>60^3 \ldots</m>  
  </p>

  <p>
    For example, the number <m>2,51,28</m> might stand for the number <m>2 \cdot 3600+51 \cdot 60 + 28 \cdot 1 = 10,288</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    Unlike the Maya, the Babylonians had no concept of <m>0</m>. Instead gaps were used to represent the empty place value. This could cause confusion because sometimes a scribe copying a tablet might not notice the gap. It was also very difficult to record two consecutive gaps as in <m>1001</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Eventually a solution was developed by using a separate symbol called a divider to indicate an empty space; however, it was only used in the middle of symbols and not at the end. Thus the symbol <m>31,6</m> (in cuneiform) might stand for <m>31\cdot 60+6*1 = 1866</m> or <m>31*60^2 + 6*60 = 111,960</m> or even as a fraction <m>31*1+6*\frac{1}{60} = 31 \frac{1}{10}</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    Oftentimes the correct value could be determined by context, but this ambiguity is a shortcoming of the Babylonian positional system.
  </p>

  <p>
    A modern convention when expressing values in the Babylonian system is to use a semicolon to separate integers from fractions and commas to separate the other places values. Thus <m>2,45,0;1 = 2 \cdot 3600 + 45 \cdot 60 + 0 \cdot 1 + 1 \cdot \frac{1}{60} = 9900 \frac{1}{60} </m>
  </p>

  <p>
    It is not clear why the Babylonians developed a base 60 system. Some historians suggest that 60 was chosen as base because it is divisible by 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6 and thus it was convenient to represent important fractions in the system. Others suggest that it was chosen because the Babylonians calculated the year as 360 days long and the higher base of 360 was lowered to 60. Another theory is that it represents a merger between peoples using a base 10 system and a base 12 system. 60 is the least common multiple of 10 and 12.
  </p>

  <p>
    Reminants of the Babylonian system can be found in the modern world. There are 60 seconds in a minute and 60 minutes in an hour and a complete revolution measures 360 degrees
  </p>
  
</subsection>

</section>
